<subSubSection id="459D5F813E9780975B06AA74EE29107A" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="108220176DAE262EF875F85B6D4E8970" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="327B19D4931C586D7C1648A52D1119E7" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">
In the revision of the New World 
<taxonomicName id="E15EDAD0A157218E7121403297182046" authorityName="Thomson" authorityYear="1858" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Ismarinae">Ismarinae</taxonomicName>
(then was treated as a subfamily of 
<taxonomicName id="BA5E64779DBDC11B0C15DD9AD05A258E" authorityName="Haliday" authorityYear="1833" class="Insecta" family="Diapriidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" phylum="? arthropoda" rank="family">Diapriidae</taxonomicName>
and contained the only genus, 
<taxonomicName id="462F29D021B8EB6DDD56F1EBA3BD84B2" authority="Haliday, 1835" authorityName="Haliday" authorityYear="1835" class="Insecta" family="Diapriidae" genus="Ismarus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ismarus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="BA63A05FBE2E9D946AA04577AFB5015A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">Ismarus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), 
<bibRefCitation id="0571742F0BB81520667B49E999E7C32F" DOI="https://doi.org/10.4039/Ent1081243-11" author="Masner, L" journalOrPublisher="Canadian Entomologist" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" pagination="1243 - 1266" refId="B14" refString="Masner, L, 1976. A revision of the Ismarinae of the New World (Hymenoptera, Proctotrupoidea, Diapriidae). Canadian Entomologist 108: 1243 - 1266, DOI: https://doi.org/10.4039/Ent1081243-11" title="A revision of the Ismarinae of the New World (Hymenoptera, Proctotrupoidea, Diapriidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.4039/Ent1081243-11" volume="108" year="1976">Masner (1976)</bibRefCitation>
pointed out that 
<taxonomicName id="782AB6FB3F0BCA6AFF6F0D503F691961" authority="Haliday, 1835" authorityName="Haliday" authorityYear="1835" class="Insecta" family="Diapriidae" genus="Ismarus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ismarus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="CA29D2F450D69621BEB5BDD863D568CC" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">Ismarus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
&quot;is usually characterized by the low insertion of antennae, transverse head, and the absence (better reduction) of notauli&quot;. This suggests that he was not certain about the status of notauli within the genus. However, in the key to subfamily of 
<taxonomicName id="63F016603A3757D1CD82595E3030488B" authorityName="Haliday" authorityYear="1833" class="Insecta" family="Diapriidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" phylum="? arthropoda" rank="family">Diapriidae</taxonomicName>
and the descriptions of the New World species, he continued to state that &quot;notauli were always present but reduced to anterior pits&quot;. Subsequent researchers followed 
<normalizedToken id="13FDA1E04889A111760C72EF2B467DA0" originalValue="Masner’s">Masner's</normalizedToken>
diagnosis of the genus and described these pits as notauli (
<bibRefCitation id="86754EA51C26632F286C217A37691AAD" DOI="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.108.768" author="Liu, J" journalOrPublisher="ZooKeys" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" pagination="49 - 60" refId="B13" refString="Liu, J, Chen, H, Xu, Z, 2011. Notes on the genus Ismarus Haliday (Hymenoptera, Diapriidae) from China. ZooKeys 108: 49 - 60, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.108.768" title="Notes on the genus Ismarus Haliday (Hymenoptera, Diapriidae) from China." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.108.768" volume="108" year="2011">Liu et al. 2011</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="0718CD29590B6BB503FC00C664E0C9EF" author="Kolyada, VA" journalOrPublisher="Far Eastern Entomologist" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" pagination="1 - 19" refId="B11" refString="Kolyada, VA, Chemyreva, VG, 2016. Revision of species of the genus Ismarus Haliday, 1835 (Hymenoptera: Diaprioidea: Ismaridae) of the Russian fauna. Far Eastern Entomologist 318: 1 - 19" title="Revision of species of the genus Ismarus Haliday, 1835 (Hymenoptera: Diaprioidea: Ismaridae) of the Russian fauna." volume="318" year="2016">Kolyada and Chemyreva 2016</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="F562AE82AD401CB27F13E361A2ECCA95" DOI="https://doi.org/10.3897/afrinvertebr.59.24403" author="Kim, C-J" journalOrPublisher="African Invertebrates" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" pagination="127 - 163" refId="B9" refString="Kim, C-J, Copeland, RS, Notton, DG, 2018a. The family Ismaridae Thomson (Hymenoptera, Diaprioidea): first record for the Afrotropical region with description of fourteen new species. African Invertebrates 59 (2): 127 - 163, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3897/afrinvertebr.59.24403" title="The family Ismaridae Thomson (Hymenoptera, Diaprioidea): first record for the Afrotropical region with description of fourteen new species." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/afrinvertebr.59.24403" volume="59" year="2018 a">Kim et al. 2018a</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="0EE5314872A65C9BE6B83B2AD3E37659" DOI="https://doi.org/10.5852/ejt.2018.417" author="Kim, CJ" journalOrPublisher="European Journal of Taxonomy" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" pagination="1 - 38" refId="B10" refString="Kim, CJ, Notton, DG, Odegaard, F, Lee, JW, 2018b. Review of the Palaearctic species of Ismaridae Thomson, 1858 (Hymenoptera: Diaprioidea). European Journal of Taxonomy 417: 1 - 38, DOI: https://doi.org/10.5852/ejt.2018.417" title="Review of the Palaearctic species of Ismaridae Thomson, 1858 (Hymenoptera: Diaprioidea)." url="https://doi.org/10.5852/ejt.2018.417" volume="417" year="2018 b">b</bibRefCitation>
), except 
<bibRefCitation id="741E9B932B0ED9FF2C69F29A7D66C557" author="Kolyada, VA" journalOrPublisher="Far Eastern Entomologist" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" pagination="1 - 19" refId="B11" refString="Kolyada, VA, Chemyreva, VG, 2016. Revision of species of the genus Ismarus Haliday, 1835 (Hymenoptera: Diaprioidea: Ismaridae) of the Russian fauna. Far Eastern Entomologist 318: 1 - 19" title="Revision of species of the genus Ismarus Haliday, 1835 (Hymenoptera: Diaprioidea: Ismaridae) of the Russian fauna." volume="318" year="2016">Kolyada and Chemyreva (2016)</bibRefCitation>
described the anterior pits as the reduced notauli and the rest of the pits along the anterolateral margin of mesoscutum as part of the mesoscutual suprahumeral sulcus. We here examine these pits (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="5492962250C235EE8573E7FC370052DE" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Mesosoma, dorsal view, mshs: mesoscutual suprahumeral sulcus; nt: notaulus A Ismarus nigritrochanter Liu, Chen &amp; Xu B Ismarus halidayi Foerster C Coptera sp." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.82.62148.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/537295" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">1A, B</figureCitation>
) using scanning electron microscopy and compare them with the notauli in a species of 
<taxonomicName id="4A87CE7C858CE4799EC52268BC02670E" authorityName="Say" authorityYear="1836" class="Hexapoda" family="Diapriidae" genus="Coptera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Coptera" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="00734DD57F6210938D78D84DE8440A49" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">Coptera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Say (
<taxonomicName id="EF2635F4A2FEFE5D313F95F7C41E2C2D" authorityName="Haliday" authorityYear="1833" class="Insecta" family="Diapriidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" phylum="? arthropoda" rank="family">Diapriidae</taxonomicName>
), which has typical notauli (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="830A7F1986230F527AA948132AA93B28" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Mesosoma, dorsal view, mshs: mesoscutual suprahumeral sulcus; nt: notaulus A Ismarus nigritrochanter Liu, Chen &amp; Xu B Ismarus halidayi Foerster C Coptera sp." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.82.62148.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/537295" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">1C</figureCitation>
). The pits in 
<taxonomicName id="91AC6E0E5572B59D8BEA035DEB13A281" authority="Haliday, 1835" authorityName="Haliday" authorityYear="1835" class="Insecta" family="Diapriidae" genus="Ismarus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ismarus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="3B5F83450A3CA7F23B4DF9034CEE48C1" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">Ismarus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are along the anterolateral margin of mesoscutum where the mesoscutual suprahumeral sulcus is located in many groups of 
<taxonomicName id="AD72CCCCFB2224B6E29181D67F2CC926" authority="Haliday, 1835" authorityName="Haliday" authorityYear="1835" class="Insecta" family="Diapriidae" genus="Ismarus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Hymenoptera</taxonomicName>
and are different from the pits of the typical notauli such as found in 
<taxonomicName id="04EE6659EB96A7338A43ACD1B81E3351" genus="Coptera." lsidName="Coptera." pageId="0" pageNumber="139" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="801425EB2486E2A4B903B2D78EA50349" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">Coptera.</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
The anterior pits in 
<taxonomicName id="5EC72BCBAE90F30626A2836101E067A8" authorityName="Say" authorityYear="1836" class="Hexapoda" family="Diapriidae" genus="Coptera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Coptera" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E79E47B07873F873AF817A860B091FDB" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">Coptera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is located at the anterior margin of the longitudinal grooves of the notauli and apparently are a part of the notauli, while the pits in 
<taxonomicName id="2FDE077E093B0F7806AF62BAA36FE115" authority="Haliday, 1835" authorityName="Haliday" authorityYear="1835" class="Insecta" family="Diapriidae" genus="Ismarus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ismarus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B845E252EDDB307145620BE5EBD07741" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">Ismarus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(if they are present) are parallel to the anterolateral margin of the mesoscutum and never present as a part of any longitudinal grooves of the tmesoscutum. Therefore, we here conclude that the pits present along the anterolateral margin of the mesoscutum in 
<taxonomicName id="83988858DDC1CA5937F656A796C05819" authority="Haliday, 1835" authorityName="Haliday" authorityYear="1835" class="Insecta" family="Diapriidae" genus="Ismarus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ismarus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="DE87F911F0335947C6AE9B3E6D2BB87D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">Ismarus</emphasis>
